When Marina Larroud=C3=A9 and her husband launched their namesake company
Larroud=C3=A9, back in 2020, they pitched the shoe brand=E2=80=99s innovati=
ve model=E2=80=94a quality product that was distributed via quick drop-ship=
 delivery, all vertically integrated, with the shoes moving from the factor=
y floor to the customer=E2=80=99s home in a matter of weeks. Larroud=C3=A9,=
 herself, also had a story to sell: She was a well-liked fashion insider wh=
o had worked at Barney=E2=80=99s, the shoe brand Schutz, Style.com, and Tee=
n Vogue. Her finance guy husband, Ricardo, joined her as
C.E.O. to stand up the company=E2=80=99s operations and give the brand some=
 business cred. The Larroud=C3=A9s didn=E2=80=99t take on meaningful instit=
utional money, and instead self-financed and raised capital from friends an=
d family, giving the couple the ultimate control and ability to do their th=
ing.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

More than four years later, Larroud=C3=A9 has remained true to its promise,=
 with a business model that aims to create a
nimbler, more efficient, less wasteful way of operating a fashion company. =
Larroud=C3=A9 owns its factory in Brazil, which it opened in 2023, and has =
some 200 employees. Meanwhile, I=E2=80=99ve heard estimates that Larroud=C3=
=A9 was on pace to make $60 million in sales last year=E2=80=94a meaningful=
 accomplishment for a startup in a market dominated by endlessly capitalize=
d name-brand players. (The company declined to comment on its revenue.) It =
has largely succeeded by making shoes that are approachable for work and
casual dressing, like the Blair ( https://go.shopmy.us/p-12495847?utm_campa=
ign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-=
+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcusto=
mer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), a Mary Jane ballet flat that comes =
in more than a dozen fabrications, and the Dolly ( https://go.shopmy.us/p-1=
2496013?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_conte=
nt=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&u=
tm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), a 4.5-inch block h=
eel with a 1.5-inch platform.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Even though 80 percent of Larroud=C3=A9=E2=80=99s business
is direct to consumer, fashion is a multichannel industry, and drop-shippin=
g is an enhancement to wholesale, not a replacement. And Larroud=C3=A9, as =
a small brand, had to deal with plenty of the headaches that plague other, =
far larger businesses that work with department stores, too. Retail, after =
all, is a system that tends to reward deep-pocketed manufacturers that can =
afford to make products many quarters in advance of their sale, wait months=
 for payments, and absorb
returns=E2=80=94like the dreaded R.T.V., or return to vendor=E2=80=94and di=
scounts on unsold products. Marina Larroud=C3=A9 acknowledged =E2=80=9Chund=
reds of thousands=E2=80=9D in delayed payments from both Saks and Neiman Ma=
rcus, surmising that the slowdown stemmed from their merger. (Saks declined=
 to comment.)

=C2=A0

Anyway, in late 2024, the company changed its wholesale strategy to mimic i=
ts D.T.C. roots, pivoting away from taking large wholesale orders preseason
and instead working with department stores and larger boutiques to maintain=
 inventory control, only shipping products after they=E2=80=99d sold throug=
h the retailer=E2=80=99s website. Instead of placing orders six months in a=
dvance, they would just sell what was available from their inventory. It wa=
s a seemingly small pivot, but also a big one in a hidebound industry. =E2=
=80=9CI do think it takes someone who is an outsider,=E2=80=9D Marina told =
me recently, regarding the couple=E2=80=99s decision to drop-ship-ify their=
 wholesale
business.=C2=A0

