=C2=A0

Of course, there were setbacks as well. The company did more business in No=
vember 2024 than all of 2022, but the high volume led to shipping holdups, =
delayed refunds, and uneven customer support. Most of the volume came from =
the company=E2=80=99s D.T.C. channels, but it was hard to contain. Some of =
those gripes would
eventually find their way onto Larroud=C3=A9=E2=80=99s Instagram account.

=C2=A0

Indeed, small forecasting misses can result in meaningful delays. But rathe=
r than communicate those delays to consumers this past quarter, it seems th=
ey just=E2=80=A6 hoped it would get better. Larroud=C3=A9 did offer credits=
 to customers, but the resulting social media comments were a mess. Since t=
hen, the company has been ramping up its customer
service=E2=80=94Marina and Ricardo were also jumping in to help handle comp=
laints themselves=E2=80=94and looking for additional support. In any event,=
 it could not have been a restful holiday for the couple.

=C2=A0

Larroud=C3=A9=E2=80=99s growing pains highlight just how hard it is to rein=
vent the traditional retail model. But the company=E2=80=99s also tackling =
the industry=E2=80=99s biggest headaches head-on. Yes, yes, they still need=
 to solve their operational
challenges, but the shift away from traditional wholesale could provide a n=
ew blueprint for inventory management. In an industry grappling with invent=
ory issues, delayed payments, and changing consumer expectations, their exp=
eriment is admirable. Whether or not they succeed, they=E2=80=99re showing =
the industry what the future of fashion retail could look like.

